File: platform/browser-extension/src/side-panel-toggle.ts, lines 12-18. Currently:

chrome.sidePanel.onOpened.addListener(({ windowId }) => { openWindows.add(windowId); });
chrome.sidePanel.onClosed.addListener(({ windowId }) => { openWindows.delete(windowId); });

These APIs are Chrome 141+. On older Chrome, chrome.sidePanel exists (since 114) but onOpened/onClosed are undefined, causing a TypeError that crashes service worker initialization.

Fix: Guard with optional chaining or existence checks:

chrome.sidePanel.onOpened?.addListener(({ windowId }) => { openWindows.add(windowId); });
chrome.sidePanel.onClosed?.addListener(({ windowId }) => { openWindows.delete(windowId); });

Alternatively use if-checks for clarity. The toggleSidePanel function (which reads openWindows) should handle the case where openWindows is never populated (always empty) — in that case it should default to always opening the side panel (never toggling closed), which is the safe fallback. Check that the existing logic handles this correctly.
